  "prompt": "What is the average age of PhD graduates by discipline?",
  "response": "The average age of PhD graduates can vary by discipline, country, and individual circumstances. However, based on data from the National Science Foundation's Survey of Earned Doctorates in the United States, here are some average ages of PhD recipients by discipline:\n\n1. **Life Sciences**: The median age at which individuals receive their PhD in life sciences is around 31 years.\n\n2. **Physical Sciences and Engineering**: The median age for PhD recipients in physical sciences and engineering is slightly lower, around 29 to 30 years.\n\n3. **Social Sciences and Humanities**: PhD recipients in social sciences and humanities tend to be slightly older, with a median age around 33 to 34 years.\n\n4. **Education**: The median age for PhDs in education is higher, often around 36 years, due to the fact that many candidates have prior professional experience in teaching or related fields.\n\n5. **Business and Management**: The median age for PhDs in business and management is also higher, typically around 35 years, as many candidates have substantial work experience before pursuing their doctorate.\n\nThese figures are median ages and can vary based on factors such as part-time versus full-time study, the need to work during the PhD program, family commitments, and the specific field within a broader discipline. Additionally, these statistics are specific to the U.S. and may differ in other countries.",
